\begin{abstract}
Cross-lingual clinical summarization aims to generate accurate and clinically reliable summaries in English from doctor–patient conversations conducted in non-English languages. This task introduces difficulties in preserving factual correctness, medical entities, and critical health information while managing morphological complexity and diverse medical terminology. In this work, we examine the trustworthiness of cross-lingual clinical summarization through three dimensions: truthfulness, clinical safety, and explainability. Our results show that summarization quality deteriorates significantly for low-resource languages, highlighting disparities in reliability across linguistic settings and raising concerns about equitable deployment in multilingual healthcare environments.
