The automatic summarization of doctor-patient dialogues has emerged as a central task in clinical NLP over the past decade. Early work applied extractive and abstractive
sequence-to-sequence models to English medical conversations, with systems achieving competitive performance on structured clinical note generation. The MEDIQA-Chat 2023 shared task~\citep{abacha2023overview}
provided a large-scale evaluation benchmark for this problem, catalyzing a wave of systems that fine-tuned pre-trained dialogue summarization models and employed in-context learning with GPT-3 and GPT-4.
\citet{tang2023gersteinlab} demonstrated that fine-tuned GPT-3 and few-shot GPT-4 achieve strong ROUGE-1 and BERTScore on the Dialogue2Note subtask, while \citet{mathur2023summqa} found that GPT-4-generated summaries tend to be shorter and more abstractive than human-authored notes, highlighting a systematic coverage gap, a finding
directly replicated and quantified in our multilingual setting.

More recent work has evaluated LLMs as clinical summarizers.
\citet{vanveen2023adapted} demonstrated that domain-adapted LLMs can outperform medical experts on English clinical text summarization benchmarks.
\citet{FraileNavarro2025} conducted expert evaluations of multiple LLMs on clinical dialogue summarization, and \citet{Ferreira2025} extended this evaluation to real-world non-English data (Portuguese), finding that open-source LLMs struggle significantly with informal,
noisy patient-provider dialogues---a challenge directly amplified in our setting by the added dimension of script diversity and low resource availability. Critically, none of these works address Indian languages or the broader multilingual clinical summarization problem.

 \citet{zeng2020meddialog} introduced one of the first datasets for medical conversation summarization, covering both English and Chinese, and demonstrated the results with transformer based summarization models. \citet{tretyak2020combination} proposed an approach based on a combination of extractive and abstractive summarization. \citet{lyu2025automatic} shows the performance of clinical summarization using prompt tuning on a domain specific LLM. Clinical NLP in multilingual settings has primarily focused on entity recognition and concept normalization rather than summarization \cite{gaschi2023multilingual}.
\citet{abrar2025faithful} propose a cross-lingual framework for faithful summarization of consumer health queries using large language models. Their approach combines textrank based extraction, medical NER, and finetuned LLM.

Indian languages present distinctive challenges for NLP systems trained primarily on English and European language
corpora. \citet{gala2023indictrans2} introduced IndicTrans2, the first neural machine translation system supporting all 22 scheduled Indian languages, trained on 230 million sentence pairs and substantially outperforming prior systems across language pairs relevant to this work.
Their resource remains the state-of-the-art translation backbone for Indic language processing. For clinical NLP specifically, multilingual resources for Indian languages are scarce. 
\citet{singh2025indihealthbench} evaluated LLMs for clinical translation across Indian languages, finding that performance degrades sharply for Dravidian and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages---consistent with the zero-shot
performance gaps we report across our entity-level metrics. 

