Figure \ref{fig:example} shows an example and summary of the methods used for empirical analysis. We study the problem of clinical dialogue summarization for low-resource Indic Languages, where the input consists of multi-turn doctor-patient conversations and the output is a English clinical summary which is helpful for both patient and the doctor. %Our goal is to evaluate whether explicit reasoning-style supervision improves the quality, factuality, and clinical usefulness of summaries.
We perform analysis of direct zero-shot inference (ZS), by providing in-context examples (FS). We also perform inference by translating the dialogues into English first and then summarizing (Translated-ZS and Translated-FS).

\paragraph{Zero-Shot Inference}
Zero-shot prompting evaluates the inherent multilingual clinical summarization capability of each model without any task specific demonstrations. This provides a meaningful baseline reflecting what can be achieved simply by deploying the model.

The model is prompted only with a system instruction and the target dialogue. The prompt instructs the model to act as a clinical assistant specialized in generating structured summaries. The model is asked to generate English clinical summary, focusing on diagnosis, symptoms, investigations, treatment, and follow-up, without introducing unsupported medical claims. 



\paragraph{Few-Shot Inference}
Few-shot prompting augments the zero-shot prompt with a small number of demonstration examples, $k = 2$ in our case,  drawn from the training set. Each example consists of:
\begin{itemize}
    \item a doctor–patient dialogue, and
    \item its corresponding gold English summary.
\end{itemize}

 Few-shot prompting is applied uniformly across all three models to enable a fair comparison. The objective is to condition the model on the desired output format and clinical content structure, thereby reducing the ambiguity inherent in open-ended summarization tasks. We hypothesize that few-shot examples improve output consistency and adherence to clinical documentation norms.


\paragraph{Translation}
A well-established strategy for low-resource NLP is translate-then-process: translate the source text into a high-resource language, and apply the NLP pipeline in that language. Given the strong English summarization capabilities of both target models, we explore whether routing non-English dialogues through a high-quality neural machine translation (NMT) system before summarization yields improvements over direct multilingual inference.
The doctor-patient conversations are first translated to English using IndicTrans2 \cite{}, a state-of-the-art multilingual NMT model developed by AI4Bharat, specifically designed for Indian languages. IndicTrans2 supports translation between English and 22 scheduled Indian languages, covering all ten languages in our dataset. It achieves competitive BLEU scores on standard benchmarks for Indic language translation and has been shown to substantially outperform general-purpose translation systems on low-resource Indian language pairs. The LLM then performs the standard zeroshot summarization.

