\subsection{Evaluation}
We employ a three-tier evaluation framework designed to assess the quality of generated clinical summaries from complementary perspectives:
\begin{itemize}
    \item surface-level lexical similarity
    \item holistic quality dimensions via LLM-as-a-judge, and
    \item clinical entity-level analysis.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Automated Text Similarity Metrics}
We compute ROUGE (L) for structural n-gram overlap and BERTScore for contextual token-embedding similarity.

ROUGE measures n-gram overlap between a generated summary and the reference summary. ROUGE score provide a computationally efficient proxy for lexical fidelity. However, they are known to be insensitive to paraphrase, morphological variation, and semantic equivalence, which limits their diagnostic value for morphologically rich languages.

BERTScore computes the similarity between generated and reference summaries using contextual token embeddings. While BERTScore is robust to lexical variation and paraphrase, achieving high semantic overlap does not guarantee clinical factuality. An LLM may accurately capture conversational flow while simultaneously hallucinating a critical medication.

\paragraph{LLM-as-a-Judge Quality Assessment}
Following recent work on using large language models as evaluation proxies for text generation tasks \cite{li2025generation}.
We present an evaluation framework designed to assess the trustworthiness of cross-lingual clinical summarization systems. Trustworthiness in this context is defined along three core dimensions: truthfulness, clinical safety, and explainability.
All the prompts are provided in Appendix \ref{sec:appendix}.
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Truthfulness}: Truthfulness is defined by checking if everything in the summary correct in terms of facts, medical knowledge.
    \item \textbf{Safety}: Does the summary avoid omissions, distortions, or recommendations that could lead to harmful clinical decisions?
    \item \textbf{Explainability}: Can the model justify why information appears in the summary and link it back to the source conversation?
\end{itemize}

Each dimension is scored on a Likert scale (1–5) by a judge LLM presented with the source dialogue, the generated summary, and a structured scoring rubric.

