\section{Experiments and Results}
We evaluate multilingual clinical dialogue summarization for four settings: zero-shot, few-shot, translation-based, and fine-tuned models, where the input is a doctor–patient conversation and the output is a plain-text English clinical summary.
Dialogues may be in \textbf{English, Hindi, Marathi, Bengali, Telugu, Tamil, Kannada, Gujarati, Dogri, or Assamese}, while all reference summaries are written in English. The task requires both cross-lingual understanding and domain-specific summarization without hallucinating clinical facts. Performance is assessed using a three-tier framework comprising lexical similarity, LLM-based evaluation, and entity-level factual consistency.

We evaluate two large language models:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Mistral-7B-Instruct
    \item Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct
\end{itemize}

These models were selected to cover different model families and sizes while remaining feasible for deployment on a single 32 GB GPU memory.
