\paragraph{Translation-Based Summarization}
The translation pipeline routes non-English dialogues through IndicTrans2 for source-to-English translation, applies zero-shot English summarization using the target model. English dialogues are processed directly without translation. Table \ref{tab:translation_vs_zs} presents per-language F1 results comparing translation to zero-shot, alongside hallucination rates.
 
The translation results reveal a sharp and linguistically meaningful split. For Indo-Aryan languages with Devanagari or closely related scripts—Hindi, Marathi, and Gujarati—translation consistently improves over zero-shot for both models. Mistral-Marathi gains +0.150 F1 ($0.420 \to 0.570$), Mistral-Gujarati gains +0.171 $(0.368 \to 0.539)$, and Mistral-Hindi gains +0.111 ($0.450 \to 0.561$). These are the largest absolute F1 gains observed in the translation condition. The mechanism is direct: IndicTrans2 achieves high translation quality for Indo-Aryan pairs given their structural proximity to Hindi, the best-represented Indic language in NMT training corpora. 

Dravidian languages tell an entirely different story. Translation harms performance relative to zero-shot for Telugu and Kannada under both models, and produces only marginal gains or neutral results for Tamil. Telugu is the worst-affected: Qwen-Telugu F1 falls from $0.450 \to 0.241$ ($-0.209$), with hallucination rising from $0.463 \to 0.774$. Mistral-Telugu falls from $0.282 \to 0.200$, reaching the lowest single result in the translation condition. 

Beyond Dravidian languages, two Indo-Aryan languages—Assamese and Bengali—show severe translation degradation. Qwen-Assamese falls from $(0.553 \to 0.351)$ $(-0.203)$ and Mistral-Assamese falls from $(0.417 \to 0.275)$ $(-0.142)$. Qwen-Bengali falls from $(0.566 \to 0.369)$ $(-0.197)$. These are not Dravidian translation failures; they reflect a different problem: Bengali and Assamese share a script but have substantially different morphological and lexical properties. For Bengali, the translation hallucination rate rises from 0.375 to 0.676—nearly doubling—suggesting the English output of the translation step is distorted, overlong, or incoherent for this language.
The practical implication is that script family does not reliably predict translation quality in the IndicTrans2 pipeline. 

Translation-based summarization produces the lowest safety scores of any condition across both models, with macro-averaged safety of 2.217 (Qwen) and 2.197 (Mistral)—substantially below the already-concerning prompting baselines of 2.560 and 2.496. Telugu translation safety reaches $1.72/5.0$ (Qwen) and $1.65/5.0$ (Mistral), and Assamese translation safety falls to $1.46/5.0$ (Mistral)—the lowest safety score in the entire evaluation matrix. 

